::function_calls_01::Which statement best defines function calls in Java? {
~Overloading defines multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists.
~Variable syntax in Java defines how variables are declared, initialized, and scoped.
=A function call in Java invokes a method with arguments and optional return value.
~Compound data in Java combines multiple values into one structure, such as objects, arrays, or records.
}

::function_calls_02::Which Java construct is most directly tied to function calls? {
~A declaration includes a type, a name, and optionally an initializer.
=Method invocation syntax object.method(args) is the primary construct.
~Core language features, OOP, collections, exceptions, and tooling are essential proficiency areas.
~In Java, primitives copy values while object variables copy references.
}

::function_calls_03::Which example best demonstrates function calls in Java code? {
~Passing an object reference to a method still allows mutation of the same object.
~A proficient developer can read stack traces and locate root causes efficiently.
=Calling Math.max(a, b) is a simple function-call example.
~Overloaded constructors allow different initialization parameter sets.
}

::function_calls_04::Which is a common mistake when working with function calls? {
~A common mistake is exposing many telescoping constructors instead of clearer factories.
~A common mistake is exposing mutable internal fields directly.
~A common mistake is duplicating initialization logic instead of chaining with this(...).
=A common mistake is ignoring returned values when the method is pure.
}

::function_calls_05::Which test most directly validates function calls behavior? {
~A good test distinguishes identity checks from equality checks.
~Tests should cover each overloaded signature explicitly.
=A good test verifies both side effects and returned output of method calls.
~A test can assert that new instances start with independent state.
}

::function_calls_06::Which performance/maintainability statement about function calls is most accurate? {
~Uncontrolled modification increases coupling and bug risk.
=Excessive nested calls can reduce readability and debugging clarity.
~Small cohesive methods are easier to optimize and maintain.
~Using this clearly can improve readability in fluent APIs.
}

::function_calls_07::Which refactoring most improves code related to function calls? {
~Refactoring parameter names can reduce overuse of this.field assignments.
=Extracting intermediate variables can simplify complex method-call expressions.
~Refactoring shared setup into one canonical constructor reduces bugs.
~Refactoring with defensive copies can prevent shared-mutable-state bugs.
}

::function_calls_08::Which Java API/keyword detail is most relevant to function calls? {
~The @Override annotation helps ensure intended method definitions match parent signatures.
~super(...) is used in constructors to initialize the parent class.
=Overload resolution picks the best matching method signature at compile time.
~Optional can sometimes make nullable chain traversal safer.
}

::function_calls_09::Which debugging approach is most useful for function calls problems? {
=Breakpoints on call sites and callee methods are effective for tracing behavior.
~Debugging with this in watch expressions helps inspect current object state.
~Mutation bugs are debugged by tracing who writes to the object state.
~Profilers and logs help proficient developers diagnose performance and behavior issues.
}

::function_calls_10::Which statement about function calls is true? {
~Good method definitions express one responsibility clearly.
~Identity and equality are different concepts in Java object models.
=Clear method names make call sites self-documenting.
~Understanding reference copying is central to reasoning about Java object mutation.
}
